5. Dependency

Suppose

class Car {

    Engine engine = new Engine();

}

Car depends on Engine.

Engine is called Dependency.

6. Dependency Injection (DI)

Instead of creating dependencies inside the class,

Spring injects them.

Without DI

class Car {

    Engine engine = new Engine();

}

Car is tightly coupled.

With DI

class Car {

    private Engine engine;

    public Car(Engine engine) {
        this.engine = engine;
    }

}

Spring provides Engine object.

Types of Dependency Injection
1. Constructor Injection (Most Preferred)
@Component
class Engine {

}

@Component
class Car {

    private Engine engine;

    @Autowired
    public Car(Engine engine) {
        this.engine = engine;
    }

}
2. Setter Injection
@Component
class Car {

    private Engine engine;

    @Autowired
    public void setEngine(Engine engine) {
        this.engine = engine;
    }

}
3. Field Injection (Not Recommended)
@Component
class Car {

    @Autowired
    Engine engine;

}

Interview:

Field Injection is discouraged because

Difficult testing
Hidden dependency
Violates encapsulation
